metadata.name: Ornamental typo #44
metadata.description:
Some time ago I was looking for inspiration in my local bookstore. In the secondhand section, I found this incredible book called Grammar of Ornaments. It features ornamental patterns from all over the world. However, the page about Pompeian patterns really caught my attention. It was a composition of patterns taken from different mosaics. A patchwork of patterns that normally don't belong together, yet in this instance looked far more interesting than each pattern taken separately.

So it was decided, I was going to make a generative piece based on this visual. I used a couple patterns as a main reference and took them for a spin. After enough iterations, new patterns started to emerge. In the same time something occurred to me. What would the people, who made the reference I used, think of what I'm doing? If I'm lucky they would think it's visually pleasing. But chances are they'd think I made mistakes / faux pas.

This helped me come up with the name of the piece :  “Ornamental typo”. It’s a homage to the reference material (The grammar of ornaments) and the realisation that the final result may not be approved by the masters that came before me.


Features (drop chance) : 

- Composition type (33%) : 3 types available ( Corner / Diagonal / Grid )  
- Palette primary (3.8%) : 26 palettes available
- Palette secondary (3.8%) : 26 palettes available
- Monochrome (50%) :  whether the primary color palette match the secondary one or not 
- Condition (25%) :  4 conditions that simulate the effect of time on the piece ( Mint / Near mint / Used / Old )


Export:

Click on open live, then :
-Press “1” to save as 2000*2000 jpg 
-Press “2” to save as 4000*4000 jpg

Feel free to reach me if you need to save your piece in even higher resolutions

metadata.name: Breakers #221
metadata.description:
Companion project to Neural Collapse (#15780), for the collectors of my previous efforts.
A study on the repetition and stacking of a simple dynamic structure, this time inside a cylinder.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.

Interactivity : 
- You can click on each individual breaker to open or close them. The problem is it will toggle others.
- Press and hold the mouse button to slightly move the viewpoint. The previous interaction not being disabled while doing that, you get some switching all over the place as a bonus bug/feature.

- Press "a" to increase quality of the antialiasing (3 levels), at the cost of performances. If you don't like jaggies and your machine can take it.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels. I recommend starting with "4".

GPU recommended. Best performances on Chrome in general.

metadata.name: ONE WORD (Ed.1) #17
metadata.description:
Inspired by the cut-up technique by William S. Burroughs, which was later used by David Bowie to create some of his song lyrics.

It generates a sequential list of a few hundred words that are placed at random locations on the canvas without overlapping.

Under the hood, a home-built spatial subdivision algorithm is used to look for empty spaces where the next random word might fit.

Originally, the plan was to publish this work with categorized words that somehow fit together into a theme, but after playing around with it, I found that this didn't match the original idea of the cut-up technique.
Also, it was very interesting to see completely arbitrary and unrelated words close together, forming incomplete fragments of a possible sentence. Just use your imagination!

The list of words was created while thinking about the current situation in the world and reading the news. Note, however, that it may happen that some words close to each other form a strange combination.

Press [S] to save in high resolution (long side = 4096 pixels).

Features:

Format - Portrait 40%, Landscape 40%, Square 20%
Canvas - Black 50%, White 50%
Background - Black 50%, White 50%
Post-Effects - None 33%, Light 33%, Strong 33%
Color Drop - Normal 50%, Inverse 50%

made with typescript and pixi.js


2022 // Karuma

metadata.name: Chaotic Growth #33
metadata.description:
Chaotic growth is based on a modified version of the differential line algorithm by Anders Hoff [1]. This algorithm uses an attraction-repulsion-model to imitate growth on a connected set of nodes. 

In this piece I explored an adaption of this algorithm attempting to visualize systems growing past their point of sustainability, creating new dynamics and eventually spiraling out of control. Some iterations may grow smoothly for some time but will quickly turn into a chaotic system of unsustainable growth. The smooth and organic shape of growth in the beginning is contrasted by the spikey, incoherent offshoots. 


Created in Vanilla JS.

Controls:
S - Save image
Space - Pause/Unpause


Best viewed in Chrome. Different browsers may produce slightly different outputs.

[1] https://inconvergent.net/generative/differential-line/

metadata.name: Whisper #263
metadata.description:
Abstract forms built with noise and texture

-------------

A note on rendering times: *Whisper has a lot going on*. It can take up to 1-5 minutes to fully render, depending on your hardware configuration, including a 15sec-1min loading phase during which lots of calculations take place (but no visuals). It'll get there, just be patient! A small loading bar along the bottom also shows the progression of the render during the drawing phase.

Press 'S' or click "Save image" to save a PNG version of the artwork while in full-screen/IPFS view

Customisation
-------------

The following parameters can be adjusted in full-screen mode.
Open the token in full-screen/IPFS mode, and add any of these to the URL:

&size=2000 (replace 2000 with any value up to around 8000) - this sets the resolution/width of the canvas in pixels. Use this to generate very large PNG images (50MB+) suitable for printing at large DPI & canvas sizes. The max value here is dependent on your hardware, might not work on mobiles etc.

&ratio=1.4 (any value between 1 and 2, default = 1.4) - set the aspect ratio of the work. By default Whisper renders at 1:1.4 but you can change this to match other printing formats. Different ratios will produce slightly different outputs, but the overall character of the artwork should still be present. Landscape mode is not supported.

metadata.name: Breeding Grounds #240
metadata.description:
Social Networks.
Molecular Clouds.
Neuronal Circuitries.
Quantum Mechanical Structures.

Blurring Boundaries.
Infinite Self-Similarities.

Total.
Mess.

Perfect.
Order.

/////
Each element (besides the painting ground textures) is based on the underlying subdivided grid which is sometimes exposed like some kind of preliminary drawing.

Note on the split:
After seeing some of the outputs, Sermin had a dream about “Breeding Grounds” and I decided to incorporate events and feelings from her dream into the project. That's how the names of the color palettes came about. Thank you for naming them, Sermin!

Press 's' to save a .png with the current resolution (2000x3000).
If you want a file with higher resolution and/or without the “Painting Ground Textures” for printing please contact me via Twitter or Discord. 

/////
Created with p5.js

Twitter: @serminmin / @pxlshrd
